South African Stocks Fall: Optimum Coal Decline For Sixth Day Amid Strike

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-07-21T16:03:42Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-21/south-african-stocks-anglo-billiton-famous-optimum-vodacom.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
rose 69.73, or 0.2 percent, to 31,125.79 by 5 p.m. in
Johannesburg, its highest closing level since July 15.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Absa Group Ltd. (ASA)  ,  South Africa ’s largest retail
bank, rose the most in two months, gaining 3.84 rand, or 2.9
percent, to 135.69 rand. South Africa’s central bank left its
benchmark  interest rate  unchanged at a 30-year low for a fourth
consecutive meeting as the recovery in Africa’s biggest economy
falters.  African Bank Investments Ltd. (ABL)  , the South African
owner of a lender and a furniture retailer, closed at its
highest in more than two months, adding 55 cents, or 1.6
percent, to 35.80 rand.  Afgri Ltd. (AFR)  , the handler of about a third of South
Africa’s grain, fell the most in more than a year, closing 39
cents, or 5.7 percent lower, at 6.50 rand. Earnings per share
for the year to June 30 will be 35 percent to 45 percent lower
compared with the same period a year earlier, the group said in
a trading statement.  Country Bird Holdings Ltd. (CBH)  , a chicken producer,
climbed the most in more than two weeks, gaining 10 cents, or
2.1 percent, to 4.80 rand. Earnings per share for the year to
June 30 will be 170 percent to 190 percent higher compared with
the same period a year ago, the group said in a trading
statement.  Famous Brands Ltd. (FBR)  , a fast-food chain holdings
company, closed at its highest since the share started trading
in November 1994, rising 85 cents, or 1.9 percent, to 45.90
rand. The group is exploring opportunities in  Nigeria , Business
Report said, citing Chief Executive Officer Kevin Hedderwick.  Optimum Coal Holdings (OPT)  Ltd fell for a sixth day,
its longest losing streak since March 2010, dropping 50 cents,
or 1.9 percent, to 25.50. The coal producer faces a strike over
pay at its mines, the  National Union of Mineworkers  said
yesterday.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s largest maker of motor
fuel from coal, rose for a third day, gaining 1.88 rand, or 0.5
percent, to 357 rand. Oil for September delivery on the  New York
Mercantile Exchange  rose as much as 1.8 percent to 100.16
dollars a barrel in  New York .  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
